Part 9

Rohan had applied for the Nandyal site engineer position using the name *Ahujaa.*

One extra 'a.' He had thought about it for two days — considered *Ahoja,* considered leaving the surname field blank, considered writing only his first name, which the form didn't allow. The extra 'a' changed nothing about the pronunciation, gave nothing away to a casual reader, and if he was hired on merit alone, would simply be corrected as a spelling error and nobody would need to know.

The HR department of Ahuja Industries connected the application to the family name in approximately two minutes. The hiring manager, Mrs. Patnaik, noted it in the margin of her review sheet, set it aside, and called the shortlisted candidates in alphabetical order. She interviewed them in order of merit. Rohan was the best candidate. She offered him the job.

She never mentioned the extra 'a.' He never asked.

Rohan found out three years later, in a car, from Suresh, who mentioned it with the ease of someone who assumes everyone already knows something and is only now saying it aloud.

"Mrs. Patnaik always knew," Suresh said, looking out the window at the passing highway. "She told me once. She said: *that boy with the extra 'a' was the most qualified we had seen in two years. I wasn't going to disqualify him for being careful.*"

Rohan said nothing for the rest of that drive. He looked at the red Nandyal dust on the verge, at the green of the teak plantations between the fields.

That evening he called Meena. She picked up on the second ring. He didn't say anything for a moment. She waited, which she had learned to do.

"The dal last night," he said finally. "It was very good."

Meena had made dal from the same recipe she always used. She knew this was not about the dal. She said: "I know, Rohan."

He hung up. She sat with the phone for a moment, then went back to where their daughter was doing homework at the kitchen table and helped her with the division problem she was stuck on, and said nothing further about the phone call.

In Rohan's application file, which Mrs. Patnaik had kept in a drawer in the HR archive room, the surname on the original form still read: *Ahujaa.*

One extra letter. For a man who spent years trying not to be in his brother's shadow, it was the most honest thing he had ever written on an official document.

---

The phone call came the next morning, before Vikram had finished his first cup of tea at the desk.

"Bhaiya," Meena's voice said. She was Rohan's wife, and her voice sounded tight and fast, in the way voices get when they have been holding themselves together only for the length of a phone call. "Please... don't panic. But Rohan has been arrested by the local police."

"Arrested?" Vikram sat up, setting his cup down. "For what?"

"They are saying illegal transactions, tender bypass, false documents—all false, bhaiya, I swear on our daughter, all of it is false," she sobbed. "Rohan wouldn't sign off on the Nandyal plant construction certificate. The contractor's concrete mixing ratio was weak, and Rohan caught it himself. He refused to certify it. Yesterday, the contractor's men came to the site office to threaten him, and today the police came to our house with a warrant."

Vikram sat very still, the receiver pressed against his ear, watching the tea cool in front of him.

"He took that Nandyal site engineer job on his own," Meena said, her voice quieter now, almost apologetic, as if this fact embarrassed her on his behalf. "He wouldn't let me tell you he had applied for it. He wanted to clear the selection without anyone knowing whose brother he was."

"I know," Vikram said.

"Please don't tell Papa, bhaiya," she whispered. "His heart condition—please, not right now."

"I won't tell him. I am coming there immediately."

---

The local police station smelled of damp old paper, dust, and stale tea. A rusted ceiling fan turned too slowly to make any difference in the heat. 

Rohan was sitting on a wooden bench outside the lock-up corridor, his hands resting on his knees. He had a swollen, cut lip that he was trying to hide from the room, but he wasn't doing a very good job of it.

He looked up when Vikram walked through the main door, and something in his eyes shifted—first confusion, then a brief flash of pride, before settling on a flat silence.

"You didn't need to come here," Rohan said.

"Meena called me. Not you," Vikram said, standing in front of him.

"I told her not to call Calcutta."

"I know that too."

The sub-inspector, who had been slow and unhelpful with Meena's earlier phone calls, changed completely within four minutes of Vikram's lawyer arriving. The lawyer carried the right papers, and made the right phone calls to the right names in the district headquarters. 

Suddenly, the officer became a considerably more helpful version of himself. He offered hot tea, pulled out chairs, and delivered a long apology in the specific, polite tone reserved for men who fear they have made an expensive mistake with a powerful family.

Rohan watched all of this from his wooden bench, silent. The swelling around his lip was the only part of his face that showed any reaction. 

He had been on that same bench for four hours before Vikram arrived. Back then, before any lawyer came, before any big corporate name attached itself to his case, he was just a young site engineer who wouldn't sign a false document. He had been treated exactly like every other ordinary man who refused to sign what the local police were told to make him sign. 

Nobody had offered him a glass of tea then.

---

In the car afterward, Rohan stared out the side window without speaking for most of the drive back to the house.

"Thank you," he said finally. The words arrived stiff and heavy, like something handed over reluctantly because it was owed, rather than because he truly felt it.

"You would have done the same for me, Rohan," Vikram said.

"Would I?" Rohan said, his voice flat. He didn't turn to look at his brother. "I don't have a corporate lawyer on retainer who can make sub-inspectors pull out chairs and apologize, Vikram."

"That is not what I meant."

"I know what you meant," Rohan said, looking out at the passing trees. "But it doesn't change what I saw in that room."

Rohan didn't say what he had seen, not directly, and Vikram didn't push him to explain. 

But something had shifted in the younger brother's face somewhere between the police bench and the car. Vikram didn't have a word for it yet, and Rohan spent the rest of the drive making sure he never got the chance to ask.

---

The house was a two-storey structure with a stone compound wall and a metal gate that Rohan had chosen and paid for himself. He had bought the house before the wedding, and the fact of that ownership was something he carried with him in the way a man carries a document he has not yet found the occasion to show.

Meena came to the door when they heard the car. She had a daughter on her hip, the child no more than three, with Rohan's narrow forehead and Meena's large, dark eyes. She looked at her husband's swollen lip first, then at Vikram, and then back at Rohan.

She said nothing. In four years of marriage, she had learned to read the particular quality of Rohan's silence the way other women read their children's faces.

"Go inside and change your clothes," Rohan said to her, not looking at her, already moving toward the small room he used as a study. "The Nandyal survey drawings are on the desk. I need to go through them tonight."

Meena handed the child to the neighbor who had been watching her, and went inside.

Vikram set his bag down near the door. Through the open study door, he could see the drawings spread across the desk—rolled sheets of blueprint paper, the penciled markings in Rohan's careful, precise hand.

When Meena came back, she was wearing a dark green silk saree with a heavy gold border. She had also put her bangles on, the full set. Her hair was pressed back neatly. She stood near the doorway of the study with her hands clasped in front of her, waiting.

Rohan was sitting at the desk with a scale, checking measurements against a printed specification sheet. He didn't look up.

She stood there.

He made a note in the margin, used the eraser, and made it again. His jaw was tight under the swelling. The room was quiet except for the scratch of his pencil and the slow tick of the wall clock.

She was still standing.

Vikram looked at her. He looked at the way she had clasped her hands, the careful stillness of it, the way you hold yourself very still so that you don't make a sound in a room where sound has become a problem.

He looked away. He had seen enough to understand something he had not been meant to understand, and not enough to know what to do with it.

"I'll be at the guest house," Vikram said, from near the door.

Rohan didn't look up from the blueprint. "Have dinner before you go."

"I ate on the road."

He picked up his bag and left. The metal gate clicked shut behind him.

As he walked to the road, he looked back once at the lit window of the study. He could see the outline of Meena's shadow, still and straight near the doorframe, and Rohan's bent head above the blueprints.

The child was crying somewhere at the back of the house, softly, the way children cry when they have given up on being heard immediately.

[End of Part 9]
